<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-11-16T08:30:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-11-16T08:30:00-05:00" n="268" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d268">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">690D.91/11–1651: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in India</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bowles</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">New Delhi</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-11-16T19:00:00+05:30">November 16, 1951—7 p. m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1770. Have just completed calls on all Chiefs of Mission, and in the
                                course of each conversation I asked for an opinion on who wld win
                                honest and uninfluenced plebiscite in Kashmir. Each without
                                exception stated that India wld win; margins varied from three to
                                two to four to one. Many of these mission chiefs or their staffs
                                visited <pb facs="0441" n="1905" xml:id="pg_1905"/> Kashmir
                                recently. Amer press here, several of whom have recently visited
                                Kashmir, also agree with this analysis.</p>
                            <p>Emb estimates are more modest as to margin but no disagreement over
                                likelihood that India wld win under conditions likely to
                                prevail.</p>
                            <p>Much of India’s improved position undoubtedly due to Sheik Abdullah’s
                                land and tax reforms which have won much support among peasants.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Bowles</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>